      <details>
        <summary>Why is the Remington 700 stock so important?</summary>
        <p>The stock provides the critical interface between the shooter and the rifle. A well-designed, rigid stock ensures consistent barrel harmonics and proper ergonomics, which are essential for maximizing the rifle's inherent accuracy potential.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What are the best materials for a Remington 700 stock?</summary>
        <p>The 'best' material depends on the application. Wood offers classic aesthetics; synthetics are durable and weather-resistant; while fiberglass and carbon fiber provide the highest rigidity-to-weight ratio, favored by precision shooters.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can I replace a Remington 700 stock myself?</summary>
        <p>Yes, many aftermarket stocks are designed as 'drop-in' replacements. However, achieving optimal accuracy often requires glass bedding the action to the new stock, a process that requires some technical skill or a professional gunsmith.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is a chassis system for the Remington 700?</summary>
        <p>A chassis system is a modern, modular alternative to traditional stocks, typically made of aluminum. They offer extreme rigidity, easy attachment of accessories, and often accept detachable box magazines, making them popular for tactical and competition use.</p>
      </details>

